The Management to:

prioritize and implement the continuing projects of 20% Development Fund and require the Municipal Development Council to identify projects, programs and activities that are workable and implementable within the year to get maximum value of fund utilization considering the increasing prices of materials;

institute control mechanism to address the root cause of delay or non-implementation and facilitate timely corrective measure during the implementation cycle of the projects, programs and activities.

Recommendation:
We recommend that Management:
The Office of the Treasurer and Municipal Accountant- conduct reconciliation of their respective records in order to establish the existence, status/conditions and whereabouts of the assets;
Inventory Committee- to conduct an actual count of the inventory items and reconcile it with the records relative to the issuance of the items. Also advise the inventory team to use property tags during the count to facilitate identification and location of the PPE.
With regards to the RPCPPE-provide adequate information on the inventory reports such as complete description of the item (model, serial number, dimension, etc)., and as prescribed under Annex 49 of  the NGAS Manual.
Municipal Accountant – Registries of Public Infrastructures, working paper on the distribution of costs for road components, working paper on the determination of the depreciated replacement costs, subsidiary records for road and road components and lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each road and road components at the end of the year;
Municipal Treasurer (designated MGSO) – Local Road Inventory and Road Map and present complete Local Road Network Property Ledger Card for all roads and road components;
Municipal Engineer – Report on the complete description and cost segregation of road and road components which was the basis of the Municipal Accountant for the recognition of the Road Networks in the books of accounts at year-end; and
Inventory Committee – Report on the Physical Count of the Public Infrastructures of the LGU including the Road Network System.

Recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Issue an Order directing the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator (MPDC) to lead the preparation and submission to COA of the Quarterly Report on Government PPAs since it is one of her duties to monitor and evaluate the implementation of the different development programs, projects, and activities in the local government unit concerned in accordance with the approved development plan;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report to keep track of the progress of all PPAs within his power/jurisdiction from planning stage to implementation to completion since it is incumbent upon him as Municipal Engineer of the LGU to “administer, coordinate, supervise, and control the construction, maintenance, improvement, repair of roads, bridges, and other engineering and public works projects of the local government unit concerned” pursuant to Section 477 of RA 7160.  The MPDC should be furnished with the said report as input to the required report of COA;
Direct the Project Heads/Managers of all non-infrastructure PPAs to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report for submission to the Office of the MPDC;
Direct the Municipal Engineer and Project Heads/Managers to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant on the costs incurred of the projects for inclusion in their respective Monthly Monitoring Report; and
Require all concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013.

Recommendation:
We recommended that:
The Municipal Engineer provide an explanation as to why these projects were not completed on their target completion dates together with the variation orders and the contractors’ notices;
The LGU through the Municipal Engineering Office and other concerned offices fast track the implementation of unfinished projects and consider the imposition of liquidated damages against contractors for unreasonable delays in the completion of projects;
The LGU must direct all concerned to see to that all transactions like procurements and/or projects must not be paid by the local government if not supported with complete documentations in order to avoid suspension of the same;
The Municipal Mayor, being the immediate and primary responsible for all financial transactions and operations entered into by the municipality, ensures that laws, rules and regulations shall be strictly complied.

Recommendations:
We recommended that management should:
Stop the granting of cash advance without a legally specific purpose;
Refrain from granting additional cash advances, unless previous ones have been liquidated;
Refrain from practice of partial liquidation and improper use of accounts, namely; Advances for Operating Expenses and Due to Officers and Employees.
Formally designate Ms. Maglangit as SDO thru an Office Order;
Formulate and attach activity budget/project Proposal for two (2) months;
Liquidate and report the cash advance as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served;
Indicate the date of the liquidation reports and journal entry vouchers; and
Observe the cash disbursement process of Section 49, Chapter 3, Volume 1 of LGU-NGAS.

Recommendations:
We recommended that management should direct the Accountable Officer to:
Completely prepare the Cashbook–cash advances from October 2013 up to August 2016;
Properly fill-up/accomplish all columns of the Cashbook-cash advances using Annex 21 of Volume II of the MNGAS-LGU;
Foot and close the Cashbook-cash advances at the end of each month; and
Certify the Cashbook-cash advances at the end of each month stating the balance for a certain period.

Require the Agency Head to enforce the liquidation of cash advances thru withholding of payment of any money due from the government, as well as, to implement faithfully the policy on “No additional cash advances should be granted if existing cash advances has not been liquidated” in order that the amount will not accumulate making it difficult for the concerned officers and employees to comply the requirement of the law;

All cash advances and reimbursements should be accompanied by a certification from the Municipal Accountant to the effect that the claimant has no outstanding cash advance balance;

For those deceased officers and employees, the Municipal Mayor thru the Municipal Accountant will prepare a letter request for write-off addressed to the Commission on Audit.

In order to reduce further the above cash advances, we are reiterating the following recommendations that management should adopt to reduce the outstanding cash advances:
Require the Agency Head to enforce the liquidation of cash advances thru withholding of payment of any money due from the government, as well as, to implement faithfully the policy on “No additional cash advances should be granted if existing cash advances has not been liquidated” in order that the amount will not accumulate making it difficult for the concerned officers and employees to comply the requirement of the law;
All cash advances and reimbursements should be accompanied by a certification from the Municipal Accountant to the effect that the claimant has no outstanding cash advance balance;
For those deceased officers and employees, the Municipal Mayor thru the Municipal Accountant will prepare a letter request for write-off addressed to the Commission on Audit.
